docs.abstract: It will be the third time President Trump has given a reprieve to the nuclear agreement brokered by President Barack Obama, despite having labeled it “the worst deal ever.”
docs.snippet: It will be the third time President Trump has given a reprieve to the nuclear agreement brokered by President Barack Obama, despite having labeled it “the worst deal ever.”
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump has again stopped short of reimposing draconian sanctions on Iran that could break up its nuclear deal with world powers, two people briefed on his decision said on Thursday, but he is expected to give Congress and European allies a deadline to improve the deal or the United States will pull out of it.

headline.main: Trump Is Expected to Stop Short of Reimposing Strict Sanctions on Iran
headline.print_headline: Trump’s Plan on Iran Stops Short of New Strict Sanctions

docs.abstract: A four-minute video depicted the two leaders as heroes making history in a summer blockbuster.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump once told advisers to think of every day of his tenure as another episode in a television series. But with his landmark meeting with North Korea’s leader, Kim Jong-un, he seems to be eyeing a move up to the big screen.

headline.main: Coming Attractions: Trump Showed Kim a Faux Movie Trailer About a Transformed North Korea
headline.print_headline: Blockbuster Trailer, Full Movie to Follow, or Maybe Not

docs.abstract: The president said Syria’s patrons in Russia and Iran may also be responsible for enabling last weekend’s chemical attack. “Everybody’s going to pay a price,” he said.

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump said Monday that he might seek to hold accountable not just Syria but its patrons in Russia and Iran for a chemical weapons attack that killed dozens of people outside Damascus over the weekend, a move that could widen a geopolitical conflict already roiling the Middle East.

headline.main: After Chemical Weapons Attack in Syria, Trump Weighs Retaliation

docs.abstract: Last week’s school massacre in Florida set the well-worn machinery of America’s gun debate in motion. But angry students injected new passion into a stale fight.
docs.snippet: Last week’s school massacre in Florida set the well-worn machinery of America’s gun debate in motion. But angry students injected new passion into a stale fight.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Around 2:30 p.m. on Valentine’s Day, President Trump was in the study off the Oval Office when John F. Kelly, his chief of staff, arrived with news of a school shooting in Florida. Mr. Trump shook his head, according to an aide, and muttered, “Again.”

headline.main: Another Shooting, Another Gun Debate. Will the Outcome Be the Same?
headline.print_headline: Why This Gun Debate Is Different From the Rest

docs.abstract: Neurocore, which has received more than $5 million from Education Secretary Betsy DeVos and her husband, has agreed to stop advertising claims a review board found misleading.
docs.snippet: Neurocore, which has received more than $5 million from Education Secretary Betsy DeVos and her husband, has agreed to stop advertising claims a review board found misleading.
docs.lead_paragraph: A “brain-performance” business backed by Education Secretary Betsy DeVos has agreed to stop advertising success rates for children and adults suffering from maladies such as attention deficit disorder, depression and autism after a review found the company could not support the outcomes it was promoting.

headline.main: ‘Brain Performance’ Firm DeVos Invested in Is Hit for Misleading Claims
headline.print_headline: Brain-Function Firm Backed by DeVos Misled in Ads

docs.abstract: Republicans got the candidate they wanted to challenge Senator Claire McCaskill. Then came the governor’s lurid sex scandal, which threatens to tarnish the Senate candidacy of Josh Hawley.
docs.snippet: Republicans got the candidate they wanted to challenge Senator Claire McCaskill. Then came the governor’s lurid sex scandal, which threatens to tarnish the Senate candidacy of Josh Hawley.
docs.lead_paragraph: HANNIBAL, Mo. — Josh Hawley, Missouri’s attorney general, took the stage in this historic Mississippi River town one evening last week, the picture of what the Republican Party wanted for the coming fight to unseat Senator Claire McCaskill this November: young, telegenic and smart.

headline.main: In Missouri, Governor’s Scandal Ensnares a Republican-Leaning Senate Race
headline.print_headline: Candidate Is Ensnared by a Sex Scandal (Not His)

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — They stood not 10 feet apart in a V.I.P. box: the 58-year-old vice president of the United States and the 30-year-old sister of North Korea’s reclusive dictator, representatives of two countries locked in a stubborn, ever more perilous nuclear standoff.

headline.main: No Handshakes as Pence Avoids Kim Jong-un’s Sister at Olympics
